***************************
2.	Help files:
***************************

2.1	LPC:

There are two manuals on LPC available, and Mrpr is presently writing a new and
much improved one. I suggest you start with reading this new manual.
As it is still a draft, you can find it in the directory ~mrpr/open/lpc/.

The other manuals are:
/doc/man/general/INTRO
/doc/man/general/LPC

You can access these two files using the command 'man':
> man INTRO
> man LPC

A more extensive documentation of 'value by function calls' can be found in:
/doc/man/general/VBFC_MANUAL.

Type
> man VBFC_MANUAL
to read it.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

***************************
3.      Important commands:
***************************


***************************
3.1     allcmd:
***************************

'allcmd' gives you a list of all commands available to you. It is a very good
idea to spend a few hours to get familar with your commands.


***************************
3.2     sman:
***************************

'sman' is a very powerful tool for coders.

It enables you to find the function name of almost every function in the mudlib.
An experienced user can answer almost every question concerning the mudlib
using 'sman'.

Do not start coding before you have made yourself acquainted with this tool.
The 'help sman' file is a must!
An experienced user can answer almost every question concerning the mudlib
using 'sman'.

Do not start coding before you have made yourself acquainted with this tool.
The 'help sman' file is a must!

If you have a problem finding the information you want using 'sman', ask
someone more experienced, 'I tried to find <topic> using sman, but for some
reason I didn't manage. Can you please tell me what I did wrong?' instead of
asking on the wizline, 'What's <topic> and how does it work?'

Examples for the use of 'sman' at the end of this file.


***************************
3.3     man:
***************************

'man' is similar to 'sman', but gives info on efuns (external functions, ie
gamedriver funcitons), rules, properties, and more. Try 'man -c' to see the
available chapters.

I already used this command a few times in preceding paragraphs as it allows
quick access to important reference files.

The most important chapter is 'man general' (directory /doc/man/general/).
It contains files with rules on many different topics. You can access these
files using 'man <topic>'.

You are expected to know everything in those files, if it is relevant to your
coding. To learn eg about weapons and armours type:
> man weapon
> man armour
> man weapon_guide
> man armour_guide
and read those files before you start coding your first weapon ad your first
armour!


***************************
3.4     tracer:
***************************

The tracer is another powerful tool. With it you can do get information about
objects in the mud and call functions in the objects.

Reading 'help tracer', 'help Call', and 'help Dump' is absolutely required. If
you have any problems or questions, ask a helpful wizard to explain it to you.


***************************
3.5     ed:
***************************

The one and only editor in the mud. For a manual see 'man general ed'.


***************************
3.6     toolsoul and cmdsoul:
***************************

Souls are used to define commands. You already know souls (or at least what
can be done with them) from the souls defined by guilds. You guild commands
are defined in a soul.

There are also souls for wizards to make coding and managing the game easier.
Souls that only wizards may have are called tool souls, all others are called
command souls.

But a word of wisdom and warning:

In the old days, when I was a young wizard, almost all code for the exclusive
use of wizards (wizard tools) was considered unnecessary and thus illegal. As
it is hard to teach new tricks to old dogs, I still frown on 'wiz code'. We are
here to code for the mortals, not for ourselves!
So think twice (and think better) before you code another skill setter, wiz
line, or whatever.

Once upon a time, wizard toolsouls were illegal unless declared legal by the
by the admin. Legal toolsouls are:

/cmd/std/tracer_tool,
/d/Terel/mortricia/open/kit,
/d/Wiz/mrpr/ka/ka,
/d/Gondor/mercade/open/mgl.

'ka' contains the command 'dtell', a domain tell. This is also highly useful,
especially for the beginner, since it enables you to ask you fellow Mordor
wizards before putting a question onto the wizline.

To load a new tool soul, eg 'ka', type:
> toolsoul /d/Wiz/mrpr/ka/ka
> newhooks

'newhooks' enables the command defined by the toolsoul.

To list your toolsouls, just type
> toolsoul

