***************************
5.	Coding:
***************************

5.1	Examples and how to treat them:

Most domains in Genesis have grown over several years. In this time old wizards
left, new wizards joined, the mudlib and the gamedriver were modified.

Consequently, there is a lot of code out there that works, but is completely
unfit to be used as example if you want to write good code. Therefore, before
you use any code as example, please ask someone knowledgeable if that code is
fit to be used as example!


***************************
5.2	'inherit':
***************************

Proper use of 'inherit' saves CPU time, memory, and disk space.

Before you start coding in Kalad, you will have to have at least a basic
understanding of the concept of inheritance, and how it differs from
the precompiler directive '#include' (and from - horribile dictu - paste
and copy).

Use 'include' only if it is impossible to use 'inherit'.

Copy functions only if it is impossible to use 'include'.

Never copy a file of 100 lines just to modify 3 or 4 of them!

If you have files which differ only in a few lines (eg two neighbouring rooms,
a large and a small orc, ... ) you should consider making one common file, and
then configuring or inheriting this common file. 

If you have more than 3 of those files, you should be prepared to produce an
excellent reason to explain why you didn't create a common file.

'I didn't know how.' will not be an acceptable reason.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

***************************
6.	Directories:
***************************

In Kalad we have a structure to the directories:

The following directories are the resposebility of the Liege. Any
additions/changes must be approved by him/her first:

/d/Kalad/       -  contains files that the whole domain uses.

/d/Kalad/doc/   - contains any documents of importance to the wizards
                  of Kalad. Eg. rules, coding information.

The directories beneath are common to us all. Keep them clean!

/d/Kalad/private/ - Contains information that we want hidden for others.
                 QUESTS/ - Contains information on all quests in Kalad.
                           Any new quest must be accompanied with a
                           document here.
                 MAGIC/ - Contains information on all magical objects in
                          Kalad. Any new magical object must be accompanied
                          with a description here.
                 GUILDS/ - Contains detailed information on all guilds
                           in Kalad.

/d/Kalad/open/   Contains any information we want visible to all other wizards.
              BITS - A list of the bits used in Kalad. If you use a bit - you
                     must update this list!
              SHOPS - A list of shops in Kalad. If you make a shop - you must
                      add a description of it here.
              GUILDS - A short note on where one finds the detailed description
                       of guilds in Kalad.
              MAPS - A list of maps in Kalad. When you make an area, you must
                     also make a map of it - to aid the liege in checking it out.
                     The map should be placed in the same directory as where the
                     code is, but maps of the cities is made available to the
                     mortals, so we place those here.

      The other files in this directory is the responsebility of the Liege. If you
      have a document you think ought to be in this directory, ask the liege.

/d/Kalad/std/   Contains different standardization-files we use in Kalad.
                Files based on /std/object.c like room.c, monster.c,
                and creature.c.

/d/Kalad/lib/	Standard inheritable code for Kalad,
                not based on /std/object.c

/d/Kalad/sys/   Kalad header files,
                do not include "/d/Kalad/defs.h" any longer,
                which is kept for backwards compatibility.

/d/Kalad/obj/   Important objects in Kalad, like
                clock.c   Kalad's central clock.
                outlaw.c  A database containing all Kalad's outlaws.

/d/Kalad/common/ In this directory you will find all the areas/code that is
                 or will be open for mortals to walk in. There are several
                 branches in it, and any new branch must be approved by the
                 liege - simply because he/she needs to have control ;)
                 Each of these directories in /common must have a README file
                 in it, explaining what kind of files the directory has - and
                 a description of the area and its history relative to Kalads
                 history. We want some logic in how we structure Kalad.

/d/Kalad/<wizard name>/  These are our private directories. Yours to play with.
                         One rule though ... never place open code in your
                         private directory!

Do no longer use any of these obsolete files:

old file:                     new file:
-------------------------------------------------------------------
/d/Kalad/room_std.c      ->   /d/Kalad/std/room.c
/d/Kalad/defs.h          ->   /d/Kalad/sys/*
